#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:7
msgid "Returns: a concrete, spliced version of the current Spec"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:9
msgid ""
"When transitive is \"True\", use the dependencies from \"other\" to "
"reconcile conflicting dependencies. When transitive is \"False\", use "
"dependencies from self."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:12
msgid "For example, suppose we have the following dependency graph:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:14
msgid "T |             Z<-H"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:17
msgid ""
"Spec T depends on H and Z, and H also depends on Z. Now we want to use a "
"different H, called H'. This function can be used to splice in H' to create "
"a new spec, called T*. If H' was built with Z', then transitive \"True\" "
"will ensure H' and T* both depend on Z':"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:22
msgid "T* |             Z'<-H'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:25
msgid ""
"If transitive is \"False\", then H' and T* will both depend on the original "
"Z, resulting in a new H'*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:28
msgid "T* |             Z<-H'*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/spec.py:docstring of
#: spack.spec.Spec.splice:31
msgid ""
"Provenance of the build is tracked through the \"build_spec\" property of "
"the spliced spec and any correspondingly modified dependency specs. The "
"build specs are set to that of the original spec, so the original spec's "
"provenance is preserved unchanged."
msgstr ""

